/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * public class ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode next;
 *     ListNode() {}
 *     ListNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     ListNode(int val, ListNode next) { this.val = val; this.next = next; }
 * }
 */
class Solution {
    public ListNode removeNthFromEnd(ListNode head, int n) {
        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0,head);
        int len = getlength(head);
        ListNode cur = dummy;
        for (int i = 0; i < len - n; i++){
            cur = cur.next;
        }
        cur.next = cur.next.next;
        return dummy.next;
    }

    public int getlength(ListNode head){
        int length = 0;
        while(head != null){
            length ++;
            head = head.next;
        }
        return length;
    }
}

/*
Note:

1.	“dummy node”: In the LinkedList, we don’t need to worry about the bounds(deleting “head”) while deleting with “dummy node”. Unless, we consider about the situation might “deleting head” exclusively.
      ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0,head);
2.	 “reference”: In JAVA, “=” operator means we let new variable points to the same address of old variable instead copying the value of old variable to the new variable. 
     Which means, all the value of variables that point to same address will be altered automatically when we only modified the value of the address (changing new value to any one of variables which points to this address). 
     However, if we just let one of variables points to a new address will not change other variables which points to its old address, because moving pointer didn’t change the value of old address. 
         ListNode cur = dummy;
         dummy = dummy.next;

3.	“Get then length of LinkedList”: we can just use the “LinkedList.size()” to get the length of a LinkedList if we are using the “LinkedList Interface”.
      LinkedList<String> list = new LinkedList<String>();
    Unless, we need to define a function to get the length of LinkedList by ourself:
      public int getlength(ListNode head){
        int length = 0;
        while(head != null){
            length ++;
            head = head.next;
        }
        return length;
      }

*/
